{"title_page": "Bobby Beathard", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL player \n| image=Bobby Beathard.jpg\n| caption = Beathard in 2018\n| position = [[General manager]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1937|1|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Zanesville, Ohio]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| high_school = [[El Segundo High School|El Segundo (CA)]]\n| college = [[Cal Poly Mustangs football|Cal Poly]]\n| undraftedyear = 1959\n| pastteams =\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1959}})*\n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ([[1961 American Football League season|1961]])*\n| pastexecutive = \n* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ({{NFL Year|1963}}), ({{NFL Year|1966}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1967}}) <br> Scout\n* [[Atlanta Falcons]] ({{NFL Year|1968}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1971}}) <br> Scout\n* [[Miami Dolphins]] ({{NFL Year|1972}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1977}}) <br> Director of player personnel\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1978}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1988}}) <br> General manager \n* [[San Diego Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|1990}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2000}}) <br> General manager\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n| highlights =\n* 4\u00d7 [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl VII|VII]], [[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]], [[Super Bowl XVII|XVII]], [[Super Bowl XXII|XXII]])\n* [[80 Greatest Redskins]]\n* [[Washington Redskins Ring of Fame]]\n* [[Los Angeles Chargers Hall of Fame]]\n| nfl = BEA041411\n| HOF = bobby-beathard\n}}\n\n'''Robert King Beathard Jr.''' (born January 24, 1937) is an American former [[American football|football]] executive who was a [[general manager]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Over the course of his 38 years in the NFL, his teams competed in seven [[Super Bowl]]s (winning four times), beginning with the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] in 1966, [[Miami Dolphins]] in 1972 and 1973, [[Washington Redskins]] in 1982, 1983, and 1987, and the [[San Diego Chargers]] in 1994. He was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 2018.\n\n==Early life and playing career==\nBeathard was born in [[Zanesville, Ohio]], before moving to [[El Segundo, California]], at the age of four. He attended [[El Segundo High School]] but did not begin playing football until his sophomore year, as a [[Halfback (American football)|tailback]]. In college, he accepted a scholarship to play football for [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], but returned home after summer practices after feeling homesick. He then enrolled at [[El Camino Junior College]] for a year before enrolling at [[Cal Poly Mustangs football|Cal Poly]], where he played football as a back-up running back and later the starting [[quarterback]] and [[defensive back]], leading Cal Poly to back-to-back 9\u20131 seasons. He went undrafted in 1959 and had pre-season stints with two professional teams, but was unable to find a spot, spending his early post-college years playing [[Semi-professional|semi-pro]] football and working various non-football jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/magazine/1981/04/12/bobby-beathard/7039d520-1ef8-4142-ba40-a418948c05f5/|title=BOBBY BEATHARD|first1=Paul|last1=Attner|first2=Leonard|last2=Shapiro|date=April 12, 1981|publisher=|access-date=December 25, 2017|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref>\n\n==Executive career==\n===Scout===\nBeathard first joined pro football in 1963 as a part-time scout for the Kansas City Chiefs. He left the Chiefs briefly to scout for the [[American Football League]] and returned to Kansas City full-time in 1966. He earned his first AFL championship ring as a member of the 1966 Chiefs organization.\n\nBeathard served as a scout for the [[Atlanta Falcons]] from 1968 through 1971. In 1972, Beathard was named director of player personnel for the Miami Dolphins. The Dolphins won the following two Super Bowls.\n\n===General manager===\nIn 1978, the Washington Redskins named Beathard general manager. During his tenure in Washington, Beathard, [[Russ Grimm]], [[Joe Gibbs]], and [[Art Monk]] helped lead the Redskins to three Super Bowl appearances and two championships. In addition, the 1991 championship team for the Redskins was primarily composed of players that Beathard had brought to the Redskins. Prominent draft picks for the Redskins under his tenure include [[Art Monk]], [, [[Mark May]], [[Russ Grimm]], [[Dexter Manley]], [[Charlie Brown (wide receiver)|Charlie Brown]], [[Darrell Green]], [[Charles Mann (American football), and [[Gary Clark]]. Beathard resigned prior to the [[1989 NFL Draft]], and spent the year as a studio analyst with ''[[NFL on NBC]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doerschuk |first1=Steve |title=Bobby Beathard had to fight his way to Hog Heaven |url=https://www.cantonrep.com/sports/20180731/bobby-beathard-had-to-fight-his-way-to-hog-heaven/1 |website=CantonRep.com |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref> In 1990, Beathard joined the [[San Diego Chargers]] as general manager. In just his third season in San Diego, the organization won its first division title in more than a decade and, appeared in its first Super Bowl in 1994. He retired in 2000.\n\n==Personal life==\nBeathard resides with his wife Christine in [[Franklin, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inigo.williamson-tn.org/assessor/parcel_details.php?ndx=213871 |title=Bobby Beathard |accessdate=2011-06-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326083849/http://inigo.williamson-tn.org/assessor/parcel_details.php?ndx=213871# |archive-date=2012-03-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Beathard's younger brother, [[Pete Beathard]], was a quarterback at [[University of Southern California|USC]], the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] and the [[Houston Oilers]]. One of Beathard's sons, [[Casey Beathard]], is a [[country music]] songwriter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmi.com/musicworld/entry/234282 |title=Casey Beathard |accessdate=2007-12-28 |work=[[Broadcast Music Incorporated]]}}</ref> His other son, Kurt Beathard, is a football coach, currently the offensive coordinator for [[Illinois State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goredbirds.com/staff.aspx?staff=30|title=Illinois State Athletics|author=|date=|website=www.goredbirds.com}}</ref>  His grandson, Jeffery \"Bobo\" Beathard, played four years at Appalachian State University as a wide receiver; while other grandsons, [[C. J. Beathard]] is a quarterback for the [[San Francisco 49ers]] and [[Tucker Beathard]] is a singer-songwriter. In December 2019, another one of Beathard's grandsons, Clayton Beathard, an [[LIU Sharks]] quarterback, along with another individual; were murdered in a bar fight in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] defending a woman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/local/williamson/2019/12/22/nashville-stabbing-what-we-know-clayton-beathard-paul-trapeni/2722863001/ |title=What we know about the fatal stabbing that killed 2 outside a Midtown bar |publisher=Tennessean.com |accessdate=December 22, 2019|date=December 22, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nBeathard participated in the 1984 [[New York City Marathon]].<ref name=\"Bock\">{{cite news |title=Marathon Week can be hazardous to health |first=Hal |last=Bock |authorlink= |authorlink2= |author2= |author3= |author4= |author5= |author6= |author7= |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=O5IbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=RU4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5808%2C8680238 |format= |agency=AP |newspaper=Times-News |publisher= |location=Hendersonville, North Carolina |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |pmid= |pmd= |bibcode= |doi= |id= |date=October 26, 1984 |page=17 |pages= |at= |accessdate=January 11, 2011 |language= |trans-title=|quote= |ref=}}</ref> From 2005 to 2009, Beathard was a consecutive 5 time first place winner in the men's age 65 and over group at the World Bodysurfing Championships held annually in Oceanside, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbodysurfing.org/results_2005.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329060836/http://worldbodysurfing.org/results_2005.html |archivedate=2014-03-29 }}</ref> Beathard was inducted into the [[Cal Poly Mustangs]] Athletics Hall of Fame in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calpolymustangs.com/inside_athletics/hof/Beathard_Bobby|title=Cal Poly|website=Cal Poly|access-date=December 25, 2017}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] and [[Los Angeles Chargers Hall of Fame|Chargers Hall of Fame]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chargers.com/news/2018/02/03/longtime-chargers-gm-bobby-beathard-elected-hall-fame|title=Longtime Chargers GM Bobby Beathard Elected to Hall of Fame|date=2018-02-03|work=Los Angeles Chargers|access-date=2018-02-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Jeff|title=Joey Bosa to miss Chargers' opener with left foot injury|date=September 7, 2018|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/chargers/la-sp-chargers-joey-bosa-20180907-story.html|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Washington Redskins general manager navbox}}\n{{Los Angeles Chargers general manager navbox}}\n{{The 80 Greatest Redskins}}\n{{Washington Redskins Ring of Fame}}\n{{2018 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n{{NFL Total Access}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beathard, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons scouts]]\n[[Category:American football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:Cal Poly Mustangs football players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs scouts]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins executives]]\n[[Category:National Football League general managers]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers executives]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins executives]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:El Segundo High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Encinitas, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zanesville, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL player \n| image=Bobby Beathard.jpg\n| caption = Beathard 